and you advance into the noon period,

89
00:06:02,041 --> 00:06:05,144
then again, you can pick from the available maps

90
00:06:06,165 --> 00:06:08,768
or you could skip directly to the afternoon

91
00:06:08,848 --> 00:06:11,030
and pick one of the available maps in the afternoon.

92
00:06:11,914 --> 00:06:16,260
Or if you skip to the evening, then you can pick one of the four maps in the evening,

93
00:06:16,400 --> 00:06:20,005
or you can even skip over and start another loop iteration from the morning.

94
00:06:20,225 --> 00:06:24,751
So again, as narrative designers, we have no idea where the player is going to go.

95
00:06:25,752 --> 00:06:27,374
And this level of choice...

96
00:06:28,295 --> 00:06:30,916
is available to the player on each loop iteration.

97
00:06:31,016 --> 00:06:34,817
So if they do one, two, three, four, or more loops,

98
00:06:34,837 --> 00:06:37,477
however long it takes them to complete the game,

99
00:06:37,878 --> 00:06:40,058
each time they have the choice of those,

100
00:06:40,298 --> 00:06:42,679
all of those maps and time periods as they please.

101
00:06:42,739 --> 00:06:44,659
They can skip time as they please, et cetera.

102
00:06:46,179 --> 00:06:50,080
So summarizing Deathloop is an FPS arcane style.

103
00:06:50,120 --> 00:06:52,901
So it has a strong component of immersive sim DNA.

104
00:06:54,022 --> 00:06:56,302
It is not a roguelike or roguelite.

105
00:06:57,602 --> 00:06:59,283
And it has the central time loop mechanic,

106
00:06:59,343 --> 00:07:01,703
which influences basically everything in the game.

107
00:07:02,243 --> 00:07:03,664
And it's gloriously non-linear.

108
00:07:04,704 --> 00:07:08,285
So our big question as narrative designers

109
00:07:08,665 --> 00:07:11,265
was, how do we design the narrative of this game

110
00:07:12,006 --> 00:07:14,286
to support this core mechanic of a time loop,

111
00:07:14,946 --> 00:07:18,547
to support all of this player choice and reward it?

112
00:07:19,247 --> 00:07:22,348
And how do we tell a relevant story in those conditions?

113
00:07:24,747 --> 00:07:34,457
So there were a lot of things that we need to think about and we tried to narrow it down and ultimately we came up with a couple of basic design goals for this project.

114
00:07:35,478 --> 00:07:42,125
And right now it looks very top-down, but this is not what it looked like when we were designing it.

115
00:07:43,439 --> 00:07:44,619
you know, evolved organically.

116
00:07:45,599 --> 00:07:48,740
So our main, our first design goal was that

117
00:07:48,880 --> 00:07:51,401
players must feel that they are in the time loop,

118
00:07:51,641 --> 00:07:54,042
as opposed to a game where if you die, you respawn,

119
00:07:54,162 --> 00:07:56,163
or you, you know, load up an earlier save game

120
00:07:56,203 --> 00:07:56,723
or something like that.

121
00:07:56,883 --> 00:07:59,083
It needed to feel like a time loop story.

122
00:07:59,103 --> 00:08:01,584
In other words, we need to pay off the core fantasy.

123
00:08:02,545 --> 00:08:05,646
So the player must feel that they are in a time loop

124
00:08:05,666 --> 00:08:06,826
and they're looking for a way out of it.

125
00:08:08,227 --> 00:08:12,849
So in that, to achieve this, we tried to create a new normal for the player.

126
00:08:12,929 --> 00:08:14,830
We tried to make the time loop feel normal.

127
00:08:15,850 --> 00:08:18,731
So the time loop is actually mentioned absolutely everywhere.

128
00:08:18,771 --> 00:08:21,832
It's on graffiti, people talk about it, it's in advertisements,

129
00:08:22,513 --> 00:08:26,354
it's in virtually everywhere you go, there's a mention of the time loop.

130
00:08:26,374 --> 00:08:30,476
So obviously, the NPCs are aware of the existence of the time loop.

131
00:08:30,496 --> 00:08:31,536
They know that they're in it.

132
00:08:32,056 --> 00:08:34,757
They are just unaware how long it has been going.

133
00:08:36,284 --> 00:08:38,386
they still think it's the first day.

134
00:08:38,606 --> 00:08:39,868
And the next morning they wake up

135
00:08:39,908 --> 00:08:41,430
and they still think it's the first day.

136
00:08:43,212 --> 00:08:46,475
So unlike Groundhog Day, for instance,

137
00:08:47,276 --> 00:08:49,178
where people are unaware that they're stuck

138
00:08:49,218 --> 00:08:51,881
in this repeating cycle,

139
00:08:53,823 --> 00:08:56,166
here, the NPCs are aware that they're in a time loop,

140
00:08:56,226 --> 00:08:58,028
but they don't know how long it's been going.

141
00:08:58,990 --> 00:09:05,297
And so we are enforcing several ideas that are typical of a time loop story, and we are just

142
00:09:05,397 --> 00:09:11,383
executing them differently. So for instance, everything is replenished the next day. So

143
00:09:11,483 --> 00:09:16,327
there is no money, no possessions, because everything you take, everything you use,

144
00:09:16,527 --> 00:09:17,929
everything you destroy...

145
00:09:18,852 --> 00:09:22,373
is going to be there the next day, just unchanged, unharmed,

146
00:09:22,533 --> 00:09:24,814
completely back to its original state.

147
00:09:25,734 --> 00:09:27,135
And this is also true for people.

148
00:09:27,275 --> 00:09:30,816
So anybody who dies wakes up the next morning,

149
00:09:30,856 --> 00:09:31,836
and they're bright as rain.

150
00:09:32,437 --> 00:09:34,717
So that's why actually Colt, in order to break the loop,

151
00:09:34,737 --> 00:09:36,878
he needs to kill all of those visionaries

152
00:09:37,278 --> 00:09:38,218
within a single day.

153
00:09:38,258 --> 00:09:40,459
Because if he only kills like three or four of them

154
00:09:40,499 --> 00:09:43,800
during a day, they will be revived the next morning.

155
00:09:44,020 --> 00:09:48,081
So he needs to accomplish this task while the day is on.

156
00:09:49,518 --> 00:09:53,859
And so by doing those things in multiple places,

157
00:09:54,940 --> 00:09:57,520
we are establishing the rules of the time loop.

158
00:09:57,780 --> 00:09:59,080
And now that we have the rules,

159
00:09:59,140 --> 00:10:02,561
we can stick to them to create a feeling of consistency

160
00:10:03,241 --> 00:10:04,421
of the setting that, you know,

161
00:10:04,441 --> 00:10:05,862
there are rules of the time loop

162
00:10:06,022 --> 00:10:08,422
and the world operates according to those rules.

163
00:10:08,502 --> 00:10:12,703
So any choices that the player does, makes during the day,

164
00:10:13,623 --> 00:10:17,664
they persist and then they are reset on the next morning.

165
00:10:18,687 --> 00:10:21,950
And it boosts intentionality.

166
00:10:22,370 --> 00:10:25,753
So intentionality is something that is extremely important in an arcane game.

167
00:10:26,806 --> 00:10:29,248
because we want the player to be able to formulate a plan

168
00:10:29,348 --> 00:10:31,611
and then execute it based on the information that they have.

169
00:10:32,191 --> 00:10:33,993
And in a time loop, this works really well

170
00:10:34,073 --> 00:10:37,336
because you repeat the same environments all the time.

171
00:10:37,377 --> 00:10:40,340
You see the same things happen all the time in the same way.

172
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:43,963
So that gives you mastery over the environment.

173
00:10:43,983 --> 00:10:45,765
You can anticipate what's going to happen

174
00:10:45,805 --> 00:10:47,106
because you've already seen it.

175
00:10:47,667 --> 00:10:50,150
Everybody else has done it before, but they don't remember.

176
00:10:51,925 --> 00:10:55,588
and actually made things cheaper in production overall

177
00:10:55,908 --> 00:11:00,551
because fewer speech variations and less reactivity

178
00:11:00,991 --> 00:11:04,914
because even though you revisit the same location

179
00:11:04,974 --> 00:11:07,255
over and over again, those are always the same people

180
00:11:07,295 --> 00:11:08,636
and they always do the same thing.

181
00:11:08,716 --> 00:11:11,458
And it's important that they always do the same thing

182
00:11:11,718 --> 00:11:13,359
to maintain the solution of a time loop.

183
00:11:15,835 --> 00:11:22,522
So we actually needed to write fewer variations than we would have if, for instance, we were making a linear game,

184
00:11:22,542 --> 00:11:29,568
you know, with a linear passage of time, and you would revisit a certain area and people would need to remember that you've been there already.

185
00:11:31,559 --> 00:11:36,044
So our second goal was that players must progress despite the time loop.

186
00:11:36,545 --> 00:11:39,769
So we have this time loop that repeats infallibly each time,

187
00:11:40,249 --> 00:11:42,012
but we still, in this environment,

188
00:11:42,052 --> 00:11:44,655
we need to give the player a sense that they are progressing in the story.

189
00:11:46,090 --> 00:11:53,213
And to us, the most important thing here was to have a unity of player and the player character in terms of their memory.

190
00:11:53,673 --> 00:12:00,675
So the player starts playing the game, they have never seen it before, so they start taking this world in,

191
00:12:01,196 --> 00:12:04,317
and so must the hero, they must be aligned at any point.

192
00:12:04,377 --> 00:12:06,498
Because if the hero knows more than the player does...

193
00:12:07,158 --> 00:12:10,360
then the player feels like they maybe did a bad job following the story,

194
00:12:10,720 --> 00:12:11,721
and that creates a disconnect.

195
00:12:12,101 --> 00:12:13,902
And we didn't want that, absolutely.

196
00:12:13,962 --> 00:12:17,084
So we need to make sure each time that the hero

197
00:12:17,604 --> 00:12:19,345
knows exactly the same things as the player.

198
00:12:21,006 --> 00:12:22,807
So the hero in our game is Amnesiac.

199
00:12:23,328 --> 00:12:24,208
He's an Amnesiac.

200
00:12:24,609 --> 00:12:24,789
And...

201
00:12:25,909 --> 00:12:27,230
But that created a problem.

202
00:12:27,350 --> 00:12:31,052
Why would our hero suddenly start remembering

203
00:12:31,133 --> 00:12:32,633
now that you start playing him,

204
00:12:33,614 --> 00:12:35,455
although this loop has been going on for...

205
00:12:36,642 --> 00:12:37,503
God knows how long.

206
00:12:38,624 --> 00:12:41,967
So we actually wrote it into the backstory of Cult, Our Hero,

207
00:12:43,529 --> 00:12:46,571
a cycle of amnesia where he forgets everything,

208
00:12:46,671 --> 00:12:49,214
and then he goes back into a period

209
00:12:49,254 --> 00:12:50,575
where he starts remembering things.

210
00:12:51,196 --> 00:12:54,639
And this is where we introduced what

211
00:12:54,679 --> 00:12:56,180
we call the pre-intro scene.

212
00:12:56,841 --> 00:12:58,322
And that's a scene where Juliana.

213
00:12:59,263 --> 00:13:01,565
A picture here is murdering Colt with a machete.

214
00:13:02,366 --> 00:13:04,608
And that is the very first thing that you see in the game.

215
00:13:04,788 --> 00:13:08,032
Then Colt wakes up on the beach, and maybe at first he

216
00:13:08,072 --> 00:13:09,813
thinks it was just a nightmare.

217
00:13:09,873 --> 00:13:14,358
But then the woman contacts him, and he realizes that.

218
00:13:15,987 --> 00:13:16,808
it actually happens.

219
00:13:16,888 --> 00:13:19,189
So the player has seen that, the player now remembers it.

220
00:13:19,429 --> 00:13:20,929
And when Colt makes reference to this,

221
00:13:21,389 --> 00:13:23,670
then the player knows what Colt is talking about.

222
00:13:23,750 --> 00:13:24,571
So they are united.

223
00:13:25,671 --> 00:13:27,552
And the player does a lot of exploration, obviously,

224
00:13:27,592 --> 00:13:28,472
to learn about the world,

225
00:13:28,592 --> 00:13:30,173
but we needed a source of information

226
00:13:30,193 --> 00:13:32,234
that would bring them up to speed more rapidly.

227
00:13:32,894 --> 00:13:34,655
And this is also Juliana, actually,

228
00:13:35,075 --> 00:13:36,936
your nemesis, your antagonist.

229
00:13:37,618 --> 00:13:42,319
of the game. She's the guide and the sounding board. And that is all thanks to the fact

230
00:13:42,360 --> 00:13:48,602
that she also has a persistent memory. She can remember from loop to loop. So we introduced

231
00:13:48,642 --> 00:13:55,444
a couple of characters who have this kind of persistent memory, but we found out that

232
00:13:55,784 --> 00:14:02,306
anybody who was not the hero or the antagonist creates actually a danger to the setting consistency.

233
00:14:04,245 --> 00:14:09,448
Because in most time loop stories, characters don't generally remember that they're in the time loop,

234
00:14:09,989 --> 00:14:13,711
unless they're the hero, and sometimes if they are the antagonist.

235
00:14:14,752 --> 00:14:20,936
Because when there is anybody else who remembers, that's an anomaly,

236
00:14:20,996 --> 00:14:24,419
and the audience starts looking for a pattern. And if they don't find anything,

