being stuck in a cycle due to immaturity. And some examples include like Charlie and Fia, who

467
00:29:44,640 --> 00:29:48,162
are a couple and they break up every day and then they get back together the next day and

468
00:29:48,182 --> 00:29:51,585
they break up again and go back together and break up again and go back together. This is

469
00:29:51,645 --> 00:29:57,329
really horrible to watch. We have Igor who has this childish dream of being a respected scientist

470
00:29:57,369 --> 00:30:04,034
but he never puts in the work to gain either respect or scientific expertise. And we have

471
00:30:04,654 --> 00:30:09,918
Alexis. If you play the game, you know that this is a man who never left puberty, basically. He is

472
00:30:10,298 --> 00:30:12,060
immature in the most literal sense of the word.

473
00:30:14,142 --> 00:30:19,867
And the challenge with visionaries was to make them likeable and hateable at the same time.

474
00:30:20,648 --> 00:30:24,931
And it was a pretty difficult balance because we wanted players to like them and be interested in

475
00:30:24,971 --> 00:30:31,797
them so they would want to know more about them. But we also wanted players to think they suck

476
00:30:32,698 --> 00:30:37,482
as people and not feel very sorry about having to kill them because the player cannot finish

477
00:30:37,502 --> 00:30:39,303
the game without killing all those visionaries.

478
00:30:40,438 --> 00:30:47,964
And the likability part was actually turned out to be pretty easy. So we gave every one of those visionaries like a big

479
00:30:47,984 --> 00:30:54,369
personality that they were all larger than life and you know pre-bombasting and everything. And that doesn't necessarily

480
00:30:54,469 --> 00:30:55,430
make them likable.

481
00:30:57,071 --> 00:30:57,231
But.

482
00:30:57,593 --> 00:30:58,554
it creates interest.

483
00:30:58,654 --> 00:31:01,054
And over time, interest creates attachment.

484
00:31:01,774 --> 00:31:03,435
And I'm saying over time, and that

485
00:31:03,635 --> 00:31:05,795
is the unique benefit of having a time loop story,

486
00:31:05,875 --> 00:31:08,855
is that you see those characters over and over again.

487
00:31:09,676 --> 00:31:14,216
And so you can get to know them better.

488
00:31:15,477 --> 00:31:17,417
And our saving grace was the humor.

489
00:31:17,877 --> 00:31:19,717
The game has a pretty light tone.

490
00:31:19,777 --> 00:31:20,418
It's very humorous.

491
00:31:21,078 --> 00:31:23,598
So we made those characters very entertaining.

492
00:31:26,605 --> 00:31:29,327
If somebody makes you laugh, you cannot fully hate them.

493
00:31:31,029 --> 00:31:35,572
And the testability part was pretty difficult on the other hand.

494
00:31:35,953 --> 00:31:39,716
So we had the original sin of the visionaries in that they are they

495
00:31:39,796 --> 00:31:44,740
escape the world to create this isolated party island that goes on for eternity.

496
00:31:44,820 --> 00:31:49,964
And they used all of the resources in towns to escape rather than to help.

497
00:31:50,805 --> 00:31:57,992
you know make the world a better place. So the very foundation of what they were doing was wrong morally. And that makes them

498
00:31:58,032 --> 00:32:01,776
acceptable targets. But that didn't really land.

499
00:32:02,444 --> 00:32:04,927
for we need something more immediate, more practical.

500
00:32:05,727 --> 00:32:08,330
So we made them pretty depraved every single one of them.

501
00:32:09,031 --> 00:32:11,714
So for instance, Frank, who is the singer and a mobster,

502
00:32:12,634 --> 00:32:13,796
he shot a man in cold blood

503
00:32:14,516 --> 00:32:16,478
for allegedly beating up his pianist

504
00:32:16,819 --> 00:32:18,741
and he claimed it was self-defense afterwards.

505
00:32:18,961 --> 00:32:20,502
And that was before the time loop started.

506
00:32:20,622 --> 00:32:23,866
So that person would not wake up the next day.

507
00:32:24,887 --> 00:32:32,053
And there's Harriet, who is leader of this cult, and she dips people in vats of corrosive gas

508
00:32:32,393 --> 00:32:41,581
just to, you know, get off. And there's obviously Alexis. So, in conclusion, I think we were pretty

509
00:32:41,661 --> 00:32:48,207
successful here. When you read the discussions online, people are saying that each of everybody

510
00:32:48,227 --> 00:32:49,928
has their favorite visionary. One of the...

511
00:32:51,491 --> 00:32:57,555
8 Visionaries is somebody's favorite and somebody felt sorry for killing one of them, but not too sorry.

512
00:32:57,635 --> 00:33:00,797
So we feel that we managed to strike a good balance there.

513
00:33:02,158 --> 00:33:07,802
And if we look at the eternalists, who are regular, mostly unnamed people who you kill by the hundreds,

514
00:33:07,842 --> 00:33:12,045
and it's really difficult to follow their stories because they die so easily and frequently.

515
00:33:13,382 --> 00:33:17,985
So we only were able to explore some of the stuck in a rut ideas

516
00:33:18,506 --> 00:33:20,327
with those characters, often, literally.

517
00:33:20,427 --> 00:33:24,910
So, you know, they start doing something really pointless

518
00:33:24,951 --> 00:33:26,632
and they say like, oh, I'm doing this thing today,

519
00:33:26,672 --> 00:33:27,893
but tomorrow it's going to be better.

520
00:33:27,913 --> 00:33:29,434
I'm just going to make it better tomorrow.

521
00:33:29,814 --> 00:33:31,135
And tomorrow never comes, obviously.

522
00:33:31,696 --> 00:33:33,737
There's only one exception, which is Pick Craxley.

523
00:33:34,317 --> 00:33:38,420
And that's one of the eternalists, one eternalist who remembers.

524
00:33:38,561 --> 00:33:39,761
This is what she looks like.

525
00:33:39,802 --> 00:33:40,542
You meet her in the game.

526
00:33:41,786 --> 00:33:42,506
in a side quest.

527
00:33:43,207 --> 00:33:46,029
And she's the only non-hostile Eternalist in the whole game.

528
00:33:47,169 --> 00:33:49,251
She is the only one person who is not wearing a mask.

529
00:33:50,211 --> 00:33:52,493
And she is sort of the voice of the Eternalist.

530
00:33:52,553 --> 00:33:55,615
So when you meet her and you talk to her,

531
00:33:55,655 --> 00:33:57,796
it's kind of a save the cat moment for a cult

532
00:33:58,277 --> 00:34:02,119
because the players understand that the cult's quest

533
00:34:02,159 --> 00:34:04,761
is no longer for the sake of cult

534
00:34:04,881 --> 00:34:05,842
or for the sake of Juliana,

535
00:34:05,882 --> 00:34:07,503
but for the sake of everybody on the island.

536
00:34:08,606 --> 00:34:13,210
Peck-Rex, he makes it clear that, oh, you know, those people, those journalists who want to kill you,

537
00:34:15,092 --> 00:34:18,396
they maybe made a mistake. They were used by this, by those visionaries,

538
00:34:18,596 --> 00:34:24,322
and they certainly don't deserve being stuck on an island for eternity, without any memory to put.

539
00:34:25,797 --> 00:34:30,359
So, for to summarize, Deathloop's story is about being stuck in a rut, as I've mentioned.

540
00:34:30,520 --> 00:34:34,141
And we have two main themes, one being stuck in a vicious cycle due to immaturity.

541
00:34:34,602 --> 00:34:38,904
And this is explored with virtually all of the characters in the game

542
00:34:39,584 --> 00:34:41,885
on different levels, more implicitly, more explicitly.

543
00:34:41,905 --> 00:34:44,446
We have the other theme of memory.

544
00:34:44,466 --> 00:34:49,129
And this theme is mostly explored with characters who have persistent memory,

545
00:34:49,149 --> 00:34:50,569
like called Julian or Pic.

546
00:34:51,742 --> 00:34:56,324
And we don't really have character arcs.

547
00:34:56,384 --> 00:34:58,944
In fact, the actions that the characters take

548
00:34:59,604 --> 00:35:00,885
illustrate their personalities.

549
00:35:01,185 --> 00:35:03,085
But those characters don't evolve over time

550
00:35:03,125 --> 00:35:05,266
because it's a time loop and they have no memory.

551
00:35:05,346 --> 00:35:10,247
So they are back to their regular selves

552
00:35:10,747 --> 00:35:11,468
on the next morning.

553
00:35:14,488 --> 00:35:16,209
So let's talk about the features.

554
00:35:18,664 --> 00:35:21,245
So our narrative systems, and we have radio calls,

555
00:35:21,405 --> 00:35:22,885
which are called in Juliana banter.

556
00:35:23,345 --> 00:35:26,506
We have floating messages, which is just floating text,

557
00:35:27,666 --> 00:35:31,366
and hammer lines, which are called one-liners

558
00:35:31,667 --> 00:35:33,327
who are made for the benefit of the player.

559
00:35:34,127 --> 00:35:35,467
And we have all sorts of systems

560
00:35:35,567 --> 00:35:37,028
that are staples of the genre,

561
00:35:37,808 --> 00:35:40,748
and that provide background lore and gameplay hints.

562
00:35:41,468 --> 00:35:44,269
So the radio calls, they sound something like this.

563
00:35:44,349 --> 00:35:45,129
I hope you have the audio.

564
00:35:45,438 --> 00:35:46,939
Frank, know you're coming. No need to thank me.

565
00:35:47,039 --> 00:35:48,840
I wouldn't do that in a million years.

566
00:35:48,940 --> 00:35:50,901
Huh. So you're going to kill your friend.

567
00:35:51,341 --> 00:35:52,021
How does that feel?

568
00:35:52,181 --> 00:35:53,802
What can I say that will make you shut up?

569
00:35:54,062 --> 00:35:54,902
Oh, so rocky.

570
00:35:55,363 --> 00:35:56,603
What are you, hungover or something?

571
00:35:56,883 --> 00:35:57,144
No.

572
00:35:57,444 --> 00:36:00,085
I know for a fact that you are, like every morning since we've met.

573
00:36:02,126 --> 00:36:04,767
Yeah, so this is what it sounds like.

574
00:36:05,007 --> 00:36:08,349
Their conversation between Colt and Juliana over the radio.

575
00:36:09,544 --> 00:36:16,891
And the intention behind the system was to have a vehicle for the narrative that would be unlikely

576
00:36:16,911 --> 00:36:20,594
to be ignored or skipped by the player. There is nothing else interesting happening when those

577
00:36:20,774 --> 00:36:21,815
conversations are happening.

578
00:36:23,200 --> 00:36:25,960
And originally the idea was that we would Frankenstein

579
00:36:25,980 --> 00:36:28,361
those conversations from a collection of openings,

580
00:36:28,421 --> 00:36:29,061
middles and ends.

581
00:36:29,821 --> 00:36:31,922
But that proved to be pretty difficult to execute

582
00:36:31,982 --> 00:36:34,923
from the technical standpoint and in writing as well.

583
00:36:36,243 --> 00:36:38,804
And we were only allowed those conversations

584
00:36:38,864 --> 00:36:39,524
at mission start.

585
00:36:39,584 --> 00:36:42,945
So we had a maximum 20 seconds before the player

586
00:36:42,985 --> 00:36:44,465
would engage it with some other content.

587
00:36:45,706 --> 00:36:51,751
And we couldn't play those conversations in combat because we couldn't swap out, you know,

588
00:36:51,811 --> 00:36:56,836
the reeds of lines for like a higher projection ones or something like that.

589
00:36:59,198 --> 00:37:04,443
And we really, really wanted to make those conversations feel as natural and as fun as

590
00:37:04,483 --> 00:37:04,823
possible.

591
00:37:06,791 --> 00:37:10,636
And we need to remember as well that both Juliana and Colt have persistent memory.

592
00:37:10,676 --> 00:37:15,001
So Juliana should remember everything that she's saying and everything that Colt is saying

593
00:37:15,842 --> 00:37:21,088
and they should not repeat anything without acknowledging that they have already said that.

594
00:37:22,349 --> 00:37:24,111
So this links back to the theme of memory.

595
00:37:25,246 --> 00:37:30,769
obviously. And in our final design, there were really short pieces of dialogue, like 15 seconds

596
00:37:30,789 --> 00:37:36,753
a piece. It was mostly style over substance to make those conversations really fun and free-flowing.

597
00:37:37,614 --> 00:37:41,876
And we only would sell you one piece of information per conversation. So they were easier

598
00:37:41,916 --> 00:37:46,659
to parse and we wouldn't have to, you know, do some kind of acrobatics to put in a lot of

599
00:37:46,699 --> 00:37:52,343
information in it. And each of those conversations only happens once. If it plays, it's gone and you

600
00:37:52,383 --> 00:37:54,284
need to reset the play through to hear it again.

601
00:37:55,506 --> 00:38:01,750
So ultimately we hit a tone that we liked, which is this snarky banter between the two characters.

602
00:38:02,791 --> 00:38:07,174
And of course there was the question of how much content we need to cover the entire game.

603
00:38:08,215 --> 00:38:13,999
So in preparation for that we listed all of the meaningful actions that the players could take

604
00:38:14,339 --> 00:38:17,342
within a map, anything that warranted some kind of reaction.

605
00:38:18,480 --> 00:38:21,363
and maybe, you know, what are the things that happen

606
00:38:21,403 --> 00:38:23,225
in those maps that the player should react to

607
00:38:23,405 --> 00:38:25,767
and would maybe want to discuss that with Giuliano.

608
00:38:27,168 --> 00:38:29,050
Also, we picked a list of interesting topics

609
00:38:29,070 --> 00:38:31,793
from the lore, the backstory of the characters and the place.

610
00:38:33,594 --> 00:38:35,035
And we had some story choke points.

611
00:38:35,076 --> 00:38:38,158
So the critical information that the player needed to find

612
00:38:38,278 --> 00:38:39,760
out before they finished the game

613
00:38:39,840 --> 00:38:41,341
to understand what the story was about.

614
00:38:42,654 --> 00:38:47,861
And that list was obviously developed in close collaboration with our campaign designer, Dana,

615
00:38:49,043 --> 00:38:54,390
to make sure that we are covering everything. And initially we had a list of about 60 of those

616
00:38:54,410 --> 00:38:58,857
conversations and then as the game evolved we ended up with about 70-75 of them.

617
00:39:00,846 --> 00:39:03,467
And only a couple of choke points have a fixed order.

618
00:39:03,507 --> 00:39:05,927
For instance, when Colt finds out that he is Julianna's father,

619
00:39:07,588 --> 00:39:11,469
it triggers a conversation and there are a couple of conversations that come after that,

620
00:39:11,509 --> 00:39:13,989
that can only play after Colt has found out this information.

621
00:39:15,310 --> 00:39:20,791
But everything else, like 90% of those conversations can happen at any time.

622
00:39:20,891 --> 00:39:23,932
So they need to be written in a way that there is no conflict,

623
00:39:23,952 --> 00:39:26,812
that they don't reference some other conversation that maybe happened

624
00:39:26,872 --> 00:39:28,453
or maybe didn't happen at this point.

625
00:39:29,978 --> 00:39:33,419
And we were testing this with a prototype that we called the Trash Talker 9000.

626
00:39:33,919 --> 00:39:38,000
And unfortunately, we don't have time to go into any detail at all about it.

627
00:39:38,520 --> 00:39:45,362
But luckily, I already did a presentation about this during the Digital Dragons conference

628
00:39:45,902 --> 00:39:48,382
two years ago, and it's called Don't Believe Everything You Think.

629
00:39:48,602 --> 00:39:54,124
And if you screen grab this slide, then you can watch it on YouTube in its entirety.

630
00:39:56,890 --> 00:40:02,515
But we executed this system with a massive linear visual script.

631
00:40:03,035 --> 00:40:05,157
It was the second biggest script of the whole game,

632
00:40:05,177 --> 00:40:08,920
and it was maintained by our scripter, Jean.

633
00:40:09,629 --> 00:40:10,790
who was not very happy about it.

634
00:40:11,350 --> 00:40:17,174
And so we had a whole list of very specific triggers

635
00:40:17,234 --> 00:40:19,656
and conditions and priorities for those conversations.

636
00:40:19,876 --> 00:40:23,018
And it needed to be enforced like really tightly

637
00:40:23,058 --> 00:40:23,678
in the script.

638
00:40:24,579 --> 00:40:27,441
And it was obviously revised multiple times

639
00:40:27,521 --> 00:40:29,762
as the game evolved and things were shifting, et cetera.

640
00:40:30,903 --> 00:40:33,724
And I wish we had invested more resources

641
00:40:34,284 --> 00:40:38,526
and more efficient nodes for Jean to use

642
00:40:39,466 --> 00:40:41,547
and some more robust debugging options

643
00:40:41,647 --> 00:40:46,209
because that would have saved us a lot of time and stress.

644
00:40:48,190 --> 00:40:50,110
So yeah, invest in your main features.

645
00:40:51,391 --> 00:40:52,131
Floating messages.

646
00:40:54,462 --> 00:40:59,464
look a little bit something like this and this is glowing non-UI text that contains vague thoughts

647
00:40:59,744 --> 00:41:05,966
and an occasional bit of useful information. Only Colt can see them but he talks to them

648
00:41:06,306 --> 00:41:11,808
and that makes it clear for the player that this is not UI, this is diegetic. And he also told

649
00:41:11,848 --> 00:41:16,970
Juliana that he's seeing those things so Juliana sometimes mentions it and that further confirms

650
00:41:16,990 --> 00:41:17,710
that this is not UI.

651
00:41:19,160 --> 00:41:22,081
And in the lore of the game, these are Colt's thoughts

652
00:41:22,141 --> 00:41:23,721
that were through the magic of the silent,

653
00:41:23,781 --> 00:41:25,462
preserved somehow across time,

654
00:41:25,582 --> 00:41:27,222
and now they're popping back up for Colt.

655
00:41:27,262 --> 00:41:31,124
These are things that Colt had already thought some time ago,

656
00:41:31,784 --> 00:41:33,564
not in this playthrough, in any case.

657
00:41:34,605 --> 00:41:35,805
And from the design perspective,

658
00:41:35,825 --> 00:41:37,326
this is a really inexpensive system

659
00:41:37,546 --> 00:41:39,466
to provide mood and gameplay hints to the player,

660
00:41:39,646 --> 00:41:40,727
because this is just text.

661
00:41:41,107 --> 00:41:42,327
We can put it anywhere in the game.

662
00:41:42,707 --> 00:41:43,608
It doesn't break save games,

663
00:41:44,688 --> 00:41:45,948
and it's cheap in localization.

664
00:41:47,905 --> 00:41:49,986
And this is an expression of the memory theme,

665
00:41:50,006 --> 00:41:52,687
because these are memories of past thoughts, obviously.

666
00:41:53,027 --> 00:41:56,008
And they also offer some reactivity to players' actions.

667
00:41:57,408 --> 00:42:01,369
And Sandra Duval, who was the lead narrative designer

668
00:42:01,409 --> 00:42:04,470
on Deathloop before I was in the company,

669
00:42:05,490 --> 00:42:07,311
she originally came up with the system,

670
00:42:07,351 --> 00:42:10,311
and she spoke briefly about it at the Narrative Innovation

671
00:42:10,351 --> 00:42:10,752
Showcase.

672
00:42:11,012 --> 00:42:12,912
So if you've seen it, good for you.

673
00:42:12,972 --> 00:42:15,313
If not, maybe you will be able to watch it again.

674
00:42:17,352 --> 00:42:22,155
So the funny thing with those messages is that initially they were not actually very reactive.

675
00:42:22,555 --> 00:42:28,117
I mean, the system that runs those messages checks display conditions on map load. So

676
00:42:29,358 --> 00:42:33,780
if you did something during the map, it would not trigger a message. It will only trigger a message

677
00:42:33,820 --> 00:42:38,563
on the next map. So for instance, if you did something in the morning, you would get some

678
00:42:38,603 --> 00:42:41,484
payoff for it in the next time period at noon.

679
00:42:42,205 --> 00:42:44,246
And that was okay in the early stages of the game

680
00:42:44,286 --> 00:42:47,489
when missions took like five to 10 minutes,

681
00:42:47,649 --> 00:42:49,411
but as the game evolved and grew bigger,

682
00:42:49,931 --> 00:42:52,053
people started spending in maps like 30, 40 minutes.

683
00:42:52,854 --> 00:42:57,818
And that was just too distant a payoff.

684
00:42:58,456 --> 00:43:03,039
to work. So we had to circumvent it with scripting. We have some messages that always pop up and they

685
00:43:03,079 --> 00:43:09,303
are provide mood and there are a couple of messages that provide reactivity. So when we first tested

686
00:43:09,343 --> 00:43:14,627
this with players we got feedback that there were way too many messages. They obscured the

687
00:43:14,867 --> 00:43:19,250
scenery which was not appreciated by our colleagues in the level art department

688
00:43:20,230 --> 00:43:25,414
and they were not very useful and therefore they were pretty forgettable.

689
00:43:26,678 --> 00:43:31,740
So we made some changes to this design, we streamlined the lore a little bit, and we

690
00:43:31,860 --> 00:43:37,463
identified four distinct moods that showcase the evolution of cults' thoughts. And actually,

691
00:43:37,503 --> 00:43:41,385
those moods were consistent with those visitor cults.

692
00:43:42,379 --> 00:43:44,640
you know, the other cults from the past they meet.

693
00:43:45,700 --> 00:43:50,702
And so for instance, if there was a cult who is like this very,

694
00:43:50,762 --> 00:43:54,944
you know, brooding, kind of, oh my god, nothing is going to work,

695
00:43:55,104 --> 00:43:58,865
but just doom and gloom cult, and we have such doom and gloom messages.

696
00:43:59,646 --> 00:44:02,327
And there's another cult who is like crazy and he just wants to kill

697
00:44:02,347 --> 00:44:04,367
everybody and he doesn't care because he doesn't remember.

698
00:44:04,548 --> 00:44:08,109
And we also have messages that kind of reflect that berserk feeling.

699
00:44:08,929 --> 00:44:12,072
And each of those moods is slightly visually different.

700
00:44:13,793 --> 00:44:15,315
We include some gameplay information,

701
00:44:15,375 --> 00:44:16,756
some, you know, pull this lever

702
00:44:16,976 --> 00:44:19,718
or watch out there are enemies nearby

703
00:44:19,879 --> 00:44:22,661
or this is a good place to snipe, this kind of thing.

704
00:44:23,542 --> 00:44:26,444
And we made those messages a lot less frequent.

705
00:44:26,704 --> 00:44:30,007
So there were fewer of them, so they would pop up more.

706
00:44:31,309 --> 00:44:34,492
And we added the time variant, which was more visually pleasing,

707
00:44:34,532 --> 00:44:36,414
because you had like one message that would pop up,

708
00:44:36,454 --> 00:44:38,716
and there was a sequence of other messages that went after it.

709
00:44:40,218 --> 00:44:43,000
And we opted for more dramatic setups overall,

710
00:44:43,060 --> 00:44:44,562
just to make them more memorable.

711
00:44:45,102 --> 00:44:47,425
And this is one example of such a dramatic setup,

712
00:44:47,445 --> 00:44:49,226
where you have this giant billboard.

713
00:44:52,109 --> 00:44:55,893
And here is how the four different moods look like.

714
00:44:57,588 --> 00:44:59,848
The difference in the visuals is pretty subtle.

715
00:45:00,328 --> 00:45:01,269
It's pretty subliminal.

716
00:45:01,929 --> 00:45:05,069
But it gives the eye something different to process.

717
00:45:05,249 --> 00:45:10,810
So immediately, it's a little bit more memorable.

718
00:45:12,771 --> 00:45:14,211
So let's talk about the hammer lines.

719
00:45:15,511 --> 00:45:17,632
And hammer lines are just one-liners

720
00:45:17,672 --> 00:45:19,532
from Colt who comments on stuff.

721
00:45:19,752 --> 00:45:21,753
And here's an example.

722
00:45:21,893 --> 00:45:23,533
And in this example, Colt is dealing

723
00:45:23,573 --> 00:45:25,153
with a voice-activated door lock.

724
00:45:29,192 --> 00:45:29,432
Ocean.

725
00:45:30,612 --> 00:45:31,173
Pearl diver.

726
00:45:31,193 --> 00:45:32,454
No, no, no, no, no, no.

727
00:45:33,114 --> 00:45:34,775
It's got to be military.

728
00:45:36,676 --> 00:45:37,096
Bomb.

729
00:45:39,058 --> 00:45:39,558
How is this?

730
00:45:41,699 --> 00:45:44,601
So yeah, these are lines spoken by Colt,

731
00:45:44,901 --> 00:45:49,144
and he comments on objectives, discoveries that he makes,

732
00:45:49,484 --> 00:45:51,305
and attracts the player's attention

733
00:45:51,345 --> 00:45:52,586
to some objects in the environment.

734
00:45:53,891 --> 00:45:58,733
And initially, we wanted to avoid this kind of thing at all costs.

735
00:45:58,793 --> 00:46:02,494
We didn't want the player to, you know, the characters just going around and say like,

736
00:46:02,534 --> 00:46:04,435
hmm, this door looks like it could be opened.

737
00:46:05,295 --> 00:46:09,136
Because we've seen it in many games and we thought that it was really unimmersive

738
00:46:09,316 --> 00:46:11,777
and because nobody talks to themselves like that.

739
00:46:13,665 --> 00:46:16,406
But when we started testing the game with players,

740
00:46:16,966 --> 00:46:20,167
it became clear that people had a really hard time

741
00:46:20,187 --> 00:46:22,227
following the story because it's plenty of discoveries,

742
00:46:22,267 --> 00:46:23,428
plenty of realizations.

743
00:46:24,308 --> 00:46:26,428
And the players were reading something

744
00:46:26,568 --> 00:46:30,109
that had this amazing reveal, et cetera,

745
00:46:30,710 --> 00:46:32,070
and it just wasn't landing.

746
00:46:32,110 --> 00:46:33,130
People were like, okay, whatever.

747
00:46:33,850 --> 00:46:36,211
And suddenly they were asking themselves,

748
00:46:36,291 --> 00:46:38,992
why does the character know something that I don't?

749
00:46:39,232 --> 00:46:42,033
Why do I have those objectives that I don't understand?

750
00:46:42,908 --> 00:46:46,109
So we tested a couple of those hammer lines,

751
00:46:46,169 --> 00:46:48,749
because you know, you hammer the player on the head with it.

752
00:46:50,589 --> 00:46:53,010
And they really worked well.

753
00:46:53,170 --> 00:46:55,270
People started grokking basically that,

754
00:46:55,570 --> 00:46:59,251
oh, something important happened here, now I understand.

755
00:47:00,551 --> 00:47:04,252
And so in the end, we added a whole bunch of those,

756
00:47:04,312 --> 00:47:07,313
like plenty, and this had a pretty interesting effect.

757
00:47:08,398 --> 00:47:15,200
on Colt as a character because it fleshed him out as a pretty chatty guy and it aligned very well

758
00:47:15,400 --> 00:47:20,561
with his persona in the radio calls where he was throwing those one-liners with Juliana.

759
00:47:21,562 --> 00:47:26,863
So my takeaway here is even if you think something is overused or doesn't really work well,

760
00:47:27,683 --> 00:47:28,983
if it aligns with your character,

761
00:47:29,795 --> 00:47:36,078
And if you really take your time to write it and try to make it original and funny and interesting,

762
00:47:36,578 --> 00:47:43,441
then it can work. And that is actually a confirmation of a very old lesson that any

763
00:47:43,501 --> 00:47:49,523
trope cliche or any overused tool can be effective if you use it well in the right context.

764
00:47:51,544 --> 00:47:53,285
So let's go through the

765
00:47:54,277 --> 00:47:59,704
the other systems. So things as notes, tapes, etc. They are known to any Arkane fan and they're

766
00:47:59,744 --> 00:48:04,770
pretty very widespread in the other games. So notes are basically collectible pieces of text

767
00:48:05,371 --> 00:48:10,277
that provide lore and gameplay information. Tapes are basically or audio logs. They're

768
00:48:10,297 --> 00:48:11,959
basically notes but with voiceover.

769
00:48:13,280 --> 00:48:16,822
Overheard conversations is when two or more NPCs discuss something

770
00:48:16,863 --> 00:48:19,204
and their conversation reveals some sort of information

771
00:48:19,945 --> 00:48:22,527
or maybe leads you to some sort of side content.

772
00:48:23,648 --> 00:48:25,729
And speaker announcements are just, you know,

773
00:48:26,190 --> 00:48:30,793
a voice oozing from a speaker and providing some information

774
00:48:30,833 --> 00:48:32,394
about content that you may have missed.

775
00:48:33,816 --> 00:48:36,718
So all of those features in Deathloop are pretty similar

776
00:48:37,759 --> 00:48:40,381
in that they have very little to no dynamic

777
00:48:40,421 --> 00:48:41,361
or reactive content.

778
00:48:42,443 --> 00:48:46,046
they are in fact the embodiment of the infallible repetition of the loop.

779
00:48:47,047 --> 00:48:50,109
They always happen at the same time, they always provide the same information,

780
00:48:50,150 --> 00:48:54,994
they always happen in the same places. And so they reflect the theme of being stuck in a cycle

781
00:48:55,314 --> 00:48:56,495
or of being in a time loop.

782
00:48:58,264 --> 00:49:03,627
So it builds familiarity of the player with the map and the lore of the game,

783
00:49:04,707 --> 00:49:05,828
and it helps them make plans.

784
00:49:05,988 --> 00:49:09,830
So because those things always happen the same way and always provide the same information,

785
00:49:09,910 --> 00:49:13,532
you can plan around them to exploit them for your own benefit.

786
00:49:15,113 --> 00:49:19,535
And we did really our best to make them as funny, varied, and original as we could,

787
00:49:20,355 --> 00:49:24,778
so you would enjoy listening to them or reading them, you know, after a hundred times, etc.

788
00:49:26,008 --> 00:49:28,709
And there's one notable variation in this system,

789
00:49:28,769 --> 00:49:29,770
which are the minicomps.

790
00:49:29,930 --> 00:49:31,591
And minicomps are those computers.

791
00:49:33,732 --> 00:49:36,614
And it's a chat system used by the visionaries that

792
00:49:36,974 --> 00:49:38,114
reacts to player actions.

793
00:49:39,215 --> 00:49:40,916
So they are, in fact, notes.

794
00:49:41,376 --> 00:49:45,358
But they're linked with sort of a script tree.

795
00:49:46,467 --> 00:49:48,950
and they are reactive to some of the actions of the player.

796
00:49:49,130 --> 00:49:52,272
So they're visionaries, they're just talking, you know, shit.

797
00:49:53,033 --> 00:49:56,075
And sometimes if somebody dies, then it loads up a note

798
00:49:56,136 --> 00:49:58,618
where this visionary who is dead is no longer present.

799
00:49:58,778 --> 00:50:00,219
And maybe some of the other characters come in,

800
00:50:00,379 --> 00:50:01,780
oh, have you heard that this guy is dead?

801
00:50:02,080 --> 00:50:03,241
Oh, I didn't know, who killed him?

802
00:50:03,582 --> 00:50:04,502
Well, called, obviously.

803
00:50:05,443 --> 00:50:10,167
And those minicoms provide very important progression information.

804
00:50:10,187 --> 00:50:11,929
They give you a lot of hints on how to break the loop.

805
00:50:13,110 --> 00:50:15,152
And they have this very unique in-game look

806
00:50:15,193 --> 00:50:16,394
with this computer, basically.

807
00:50:16,915 --> 00:50:20,479
So my takeaway here is that if you give a different aspect

808
00:50:20,519 --> 00:50:22,742
to something that is already familiar,

809
00:50:22,922 --> 00:50:25,185
you effectively make it different in the eyes of the player.

810
00:50:25,586 --> 00:50:27,548
So you can get more mileage out of the same,

811
00:50:27,929 --> 00:50:29,150
you know, gameplay system that you have.

812
00:50:30,687 --> 00:50:33,787
And minicoms reflect both main themes.

813
00:50:33,807 --> 00:50:37,608
They're stuck in a cycle because the visionaries always

814
00:50:37,648 --> 00:50:38,369
say the same thing.

815
00:50:39,369 --> 00:50:42,550
And also memory, because if the player does something weird,

816
00:50:42,630 --> 00:50:44,950
then it will comment on that.

817
00:50:45,030 --> 00:50:47,871
So it responds to player actions.

818
00:50:47,991 --> 00:50:50,792
But as soon as the next day falls over,

819
00:50:52,532 --> 00:50:53,993
it's back to the same conversation again.

820
00:50:54,033 --> 00:50:56,013
If you do nothing, they will repeat 100 times

821
00:50:56,053 --> 00:50:56,553
the same thing.

822
00:50:58,654 --> 00:50:58,854
So.

823
00:51:00,882 --> 00:51:03,664
Our main themes, which are also realizations

824
00:51:03,724 --> 00:51:05,645
of our main design goals, are expressed

825
00:51:05,805 --> 00:51:07,285
across all of the narrative systems.

826
00:51:07,746 --> 00:51:10,367
And anything that has persistent or reactive content

827
00:51:10,447 --> 00:51:12,968
links to memory, because it offers players progression.

828
00:51:13,649 --> 00:51:15,670
So radio calls, floating messages, and minicoms

829
00:51:15,810 --> 00:51:16,430
are all part of this.

830
00:51:17,190 --> 00:51:19,171
And any non-reactive content, links

831
00:51:19,191 --> 00:51:22,093
to being stuck in a cycle, illustrates the repeatability

832
00:51:22,133 --> 00:51:22,613
of the loop.

833
00:51:23,093 --> 00:51:24,774
So it gives you an impression of being in the loop.

834
00:51:24,814 --> 00:51:27,616
So those are notes, tapes, the overheard conversations,

835
00:51:27,676 --> 00:51:28,316
et cetera, et cetera.

836
00:51:29,720 --> 00:51:32,923
And so in conclusion of this talk,

837
00:51:34,724 --> 00:51:37,566
each game offers challenges because of its setting

838
00:51:37,586 --> 00:51:39,027
and its gameplay loop.

839
00:51:39,568 --> 00:51:43,190
So you as narrative designer needs to embrace that.

840
00:51:44,365 --> 00:51:49,347
and identify what are your key design problems and maybe try to align them with your themes.

841
00:51:49,867 --> 00:51:54,370
And then you can use that to orient your work because anything you do to realize a theme

842
00:51:54,790 --> 00:52:02,353
also realizes one of your design goals. And each time you try to realize a design goal and

843
00:52:02,494 --> 00:52:06,615
make sure that you're really executing it, it also illustrates your themes.

844
00:52:07,256 --> 00:52:10,798
So it gives a very consistent experience to the player.

845
00:52:12,131 --> 00:52:17,956
And in Deathloop, this was an organic process that evolved through many iteration cycles,

846
00:52:18,236 --> 00:52:21,019
and we were fortunate to have enough time to make it work.

847
00:52:22,440 --> 00:52:25,864
And we couldn't have done that without testing with players and user research.

848
00:52:26,684 --> 00:52:28,686
It was an extremely valuable tool.

849
00:52:30,055 --> 00:52:34,516
And when you have big moments, then make sure to pay them off

850
00:52:34,896 --> 00:52:39,657
correctly to the player. And if you have things that kind of go outside of the story,

851
00:52:39,677 --> 00:52:44,999
make sure to make them big moments and then pay them off. And of course, we should never forget

852
00:52:45,019 --> 00:52:50,240
the rudiments. So themes, consistency, characters, conflict, all of that is important in a time

